<pageContent>
    <id><![CDATA[OTS_SA_R4_D040]]></id>
	<title><![CDATA[<Introtext style="font-family:Helvetica; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold; color:#cc0033; margin:10px -5px 10px 5px; width:738px; padding:5px 0 5px 5px; background:#e8e8e8; border-bottom:1px solid #333; display:block;">Direction from your District Manager</Introtext>]]></title>
	<title2><![CDATA[]]></title2>
	<instructions><![CDATA[<welcomeText style=" font-family:Helvetica; font-size:11pt; line-height:18pt; text-align:justify; font-weight:bold; color:#333; display:block; margin:0 10px 10px">What is the right action to take at this time?</welcomeText >]]></instructions>
	<choices>
		<choice>
			<id><![CDATA[1]]></id>
			<isCorrect><![CDATA[YES]]></isCorrect>
			<choiceText><![CDATA[<welcomeText style=" font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; line-height:18pt; text-align:justify; font-weight:normal; color:#333; display:block; margin:0 10px 10px"><b>A</b>. Spend the time necessary to identify any concerns Dr. Cardonza and Dr. Gomez may have about initiating Samsca in the hospital and continuing treatment on an outpatient basis. This is a necessary step to help ensure that  the physicians know how to access Samsca.</welcomeText>]]></choiceText>
			<KPIs totalScore="30">
				<KPI marks="10"><![CDATA[Customer Results Score]]></KPI>
				<KPI marks="10"><![CDATA[Sales Progress Score]]></KPI>
				<KPI marks="10"><![CDATA[Trusted Advisor Relationship Score]]></KPI>
			</KPIs>
			<branchTo><![CDATA[OTS_SA_R4_D040_A010]]></branchTo>
		</choice>
		<choice>
			<id><![CDATA[2]]></id>
			<isCorrect><![CDATA[NO]]></isCorrect>
			<choiceText><![CDATA[<welcomeText style=" font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; line-height:18pt; text-align:justify; font-weight:normal; color:#333; display:block; margin:0 10px 10px"><b>B</b>. It’s time to close the sale. Stop by the Maycomb cardiology department again and meet with Dr. Cardonza, reinforcing the benefits of initiating Samsca in the hospital for appropriate patients and, when appropriate, continuing that therapy after discharge.</welcomeText>]]></choiceText>
			<KPIs totalScore="5">
				<KPI marks="5"><![CDATA[Customer Results Score]]></KPI>
				<KPI marks="5"><![CDATA[Sales Progress Score]]></KPI>
				<KPI marks="-5"><![CDATA[Trusted Advisor Relationship Score]]></KPI>
			</KPIs>
			<branchTo><![CDATA[OTS_SA_R4_D040_B010]]></branchTo>
		</choice>
		<choice>
			<id><![CDATA[3]]></id>
			<isCorrect><![CDATA[NO]]></isCorrect>
			<choiceText><![CDATA[<welcomeText style=" font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; line-height:18pt; text-align:justify; font-weight:normal; color:#333; display:block; margin:0 10px 10px"><b>C</b>. It doesn’t have to take a long time to move through the prescribing cycle. Immediately provide Dr. Cardonza the information on product coverage and patient cost, and any other information he may need to move forward with prescribing. </span></welcomeText>]]></choiceText>
			<KPIs totalScore="5">
				<KPI marks="0"><![CDATA[Customer Results Score]]></KPI>
				<KPI marks="5"><![CDATA[Sales Progress Score]]></KPI>
				<KPI marks="0"><![CDATA[Trusted Advisor Relationship Score]]></KPI>
			</KPIs>
			<branchTo><![CDATA[OTS_SA_R4_D040_B010]]></branchTo>
		</choice>
		<choice>
			<id><![CDATA[4]]></id>
			<isCorrect><![CDATA[NO]]></isCorrect>
			<choiceText><![CDATA[<welcomeText style=" font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; line-height:18pt; text-align:justify; font-weight:normal; color:#333; display:block; margin:0 10px 10px"><b>D</b>. Do more than just provide the product coverage and patient cost information.  Remind Dr. Cardonza and Dr. Gomez of the value Samsca may bring to their department by addressing their priorities.</welcomeText>]]></choiceText>
			<KPIs totalScore="10">
				<KPI marks="5"><![CDATA[Customer Results Score]]></KPI>
				<KPI marks="5"><![CDATA[Sales Progress Score]]></KPI>
				<KPI marks="0"><![CDATA[Trusted Advisor Relationship Score]]></KPI>
			</KPIs>
			<branchTo><![CDATA[OTS_SA_R4_D040_C010]]></branchTo>
		</choice>
		<!--<feedbackText><![CDATA[]]></feedbackText>-->
	</choices>
 <summary><![CDATA[<welcomeText style=" font-family:Helvetica; font-size:12pt; line-height:18pt; text-align:justify; font-weight:normal; color:#333; display:block; margin:0 10px 10px">Making sure you have addressed concerns about the possible benefits and risks of continuing treatment in the outpatient setting increases the chances that the sale will be successful (Choice A). This doesn’t have to take a long time, and you might even expand prescribing more than what the customer originally intended. Moving forward with patient cost and insurance coverage too early without giving the customer the opportunity to express any concerns about risks (Choices B and C) may prove successful in the short term, but it could slow things down later. If the customer has to identify risks on their own without your guidance, you risk damaging your position as a trusted advisor. Choice D focuses too heavily on your past relationship with the customer and your product’s value, rather than on the customer’s needs. Choice A is the best choice.</welcomeText>]]></summary>
</pageContent>